if(!window.MM) window.MM={};
window.MM['ent_p2_thyroid']=[
  {q:"The thyroid gland develops embryologically from the:",o:["First branchial pouch","Foramen cecum","Pyriform fossa","Third branchial arch","Ultimobranchial body only"],a:1,e:"The thyroid gland originates from endodermal thickening near the foramen cecum at the base of tongue. Developmental anomalies appear clinically when descent becomes incomplete or aberrant.<br><br>During embryogenesis, the gland descends anterior to the hyoid bone and laryngeal cartilages through the thyroglossal tract pathway.<br><br>First branchial pouch (option A), pyriform fossa (option C), third branchial arch (option D), and ultimobranchial body alone (option E) are incorrect origins.<br><br><em>(Recall and Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"The nerve most closely related to the superior thyroid artery during thyroid surgery is:",o:["Hypoglossal nerve","External laryngeal nerve","Recurrent laryngeal nerve","Lingual nerve","Glossopharyngeal nerve"],a:1,e:"The external laryngeal nerve runs closely with the superior thyroid artery near the upper pole of thyroid gland. Voice fatigue develops clinically after accidental nerve injury.<br><br>This nerve supplies cricothyroid muscle, which is responsible for tightening vocal cords and producing high-pitched phonation.<br><br>Hypoglossal nerve (option A), recurrent laryngeal nerve (option C), lingual nerve (option D), and glossopharyngeal nerve (option E) have different anatomical relations.<br><br><em>(Recall and Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"The thyroid gland is enclosed within the:",o:["Pretracheal fascia","Buccopharyngeal fascia","Prevertebral fascia","Carotid sheath","Investing fascia only"],a:0,e:"The thyroid gland is enclosed within pretracheal fascia, which anchors it to larynx and trachea. Swelling therefore moves clinically during deglutition.<br><br>This fascial attachment explains the characteristic upward movement of thyroid swellings during swallowing examination.<br><br>Prevertebral fascia (option C), buccopharyngeal fascia (option B), carotid sheath (option D), and investing fascia only (option E) are incorrect coverings.<br><br><em>(Snell's Clinical Anatomy)</em>"},
  {q:"The principal hormone responsible for increasing basal metabolic rate is:",o:["Thyroxine","Parathyroid hormone","Calcitonin","Insulin","Aldosterone"],a:0,e:"Thyroxine is the principal thyroid hormone responsible for increasing basal metabolic rate. Heat intolerance and weight loss develop clinically in excessive secretion states.<br><br>The hormone stimulates oxygen consumption and influences carbohydrate, protein, and lipid metabolism throughout body tissues.<br><br>Calcitonin (option C), parathyroid hormone (option B), insulin (option D), and aldosterone (option E) have different physiological functions.<br><br><em>(Guyton and Hall Physiology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient develops inability to produce high-pitched sounds after thyroidectomy. The injured nerve is:",o:["Recurrent laryngeal nerve","Hypoglossal nerve","External laryngeal nerve","Glossopharyngeal nerve","Internal laryngeal nerve"],a:2,e:"External laryngeal nerve injury produces paralysis of cricothyroid muscle with inability to produce high-pitched sounds. Voice fatigue develops clinically especially in professional speakers.<br><br>The nerve lies close to superior thyroid vessels and remains vulnerable during ligation of superior pole pedicle.<br><br>Recurrent laryngeal nerve (option A), hypoglossal nerve (option B), glossopharyngeal nerve (option D), and internal laryngeal nerve (option E) have different functions.<br><br><em>(Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"The pyramidal lobe of thyroid represents persistence of the:",o:["Branchial pouch","Ultimobranchial body","Thyroglossal duct","Tuberculum impar","Thyrohyoid membrane"],a:2,e:"The pyramidal lobe represents persistence of distal thyroglossal duct tissue. Midline upward extension develops clinically from thyroid isthmus in many individuals.<br><br>It commonly projects upward toward hyoid bone and may contain functioning thyroid tissue.<br><br>Branchial pouch (option A), ultimobranchial body (option B), tuberculum impar (option D), and thyrohyoid membrane (option E) are unrelated structures.<br><br><em>(Recall and Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"The recurrent laryngeal nerve is most closely related to the:",o:["Superior thyroid artery","Internal jugular vein","Lingual artery","Facial vein","Inferior thyroid artery"],a:4,e:"The recurrent laryngeal nerve is closely related to inferior thyroid artery near the posterior thyroid surface. Hoarseness develops clinically after accidental surgical injury.<br><br>The relationship is variable, making identification of the nerve essential during thyroid surgery.<br><br>Superior thyroid artery (option A), lingual artery (option C), facial vein (option D), and internal jugular vein (option B) are less closely related.<br><br><em>(Snell's Clinical Anatomy)</em>"},
  {q:"The parafollicular C cells of thyroid secrete:",o:["Calcitonin","Triiodothyronine","Thyroxine","TSH","Parathyroid hormone"],a:0,e:"Parafollicular C cells secrete calcitonin, which lowers serum calcium concentration. Medullary carcinoma develops clinically from malignant transformation of these cells.<br><br>Calcitonin inhibits osteoclastic bone resorption and contributes to calcium homeostasis.<br><br>Thyroxine (option C), triiodothyronine (option B), TSH (option D), and parathyroid hormone (option E) originate elsewhere.<br><br><em>(Guyton and Hall Physiology)</em>"},
  {q:"A thyroid swelling moves on swallowing because of its attachment to the:",o:["Trachea and larynx","Prevertebral fascia","Esophagus","Carotid sheath","Vertebral column"],a:0,e:"Thyroid swellings move during swallowing because the gland is attached to larynx and upper trachea. Neck masses therefore rise clinically during deglutition examination.<br><br>Berry ligament firmly anchors thyroid tissue to cricoid cartilage and upper tracheal rings.<br><br>Esophagus (option C), prevertebral fascia (option B), carotid sheath (option D), and vertebral column (option E) are less relevant attachments.<br><br><em>(Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"The isthmus of thyroid gland usually lies opposite the:",o:["First tracheal ring","Second and third tracheal rings","Fourth and fifth tracheal rings","Cricoid cartilage only","Thyrohyoid membrane"],a:1,e:"The thyroid isthmus usually overlies the second and third tracheal rings. Enlargement develops clinically as a visible midline lower neck swelling.<br><br>This anatomical relation becomes important during tracheostomy and thyroid surgery.<br><br>First tracheal ring (option A), fourth and fifth rings (option C), cricoid cartilage (option D), and thyrohyoid membrane (option E) are incorrect levels.<br><br><em>(Recall and Snell's Clinical Anatomy)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient develops bilateral vocal cord paralysis after total thyroidectomy. The injured structure is:",o:["External laryngeal nerve","Hypoglossal nerve","Recurrent laryngeal nerves","Internal laryngeal nerve","Cervical sympathetic chain"],a:2,e:"Bilateral recurrent laryngeal nerve injury produces bilateral vocal cord paralysis with airway compromise. Inspiratory stridor develops clinically soon after surgery.<br><br>The nerves supply all intrinsic laryngeal muscles except cricothyroid muscle.<br><br>External laryngeal nerve (option A), hypoglossal nerve (option B), internal laryngeal nerve (option D), and sympathetic chain (option E) have different functions.<br><br><em>(Scott-Brown's Otorhinolaryngology)</em>"},
  {q:"The superior thyroid artery arises from the:",o:["External carotid artery","Common carotid artery","Subclavian artery","Internal carotid artery","Vertebral artery"],a:0,e:"The superior thyroid artery usually arises from external carotid artery near carotid bifurcation. Significant hemorrhage develops clinically if vessel control becomes inadequate during surgery.<br><br>It descends toward upper thyroid pole accompanied by external laryngeal nerve.<br><br>Subclavian artery (option C), common carotid artery (option B), internal carotid artery (option D), and vertebral artery (option E) are incorrect origins.<br><br><em>(Snell's Clinical Anatomy)</em>"},
  {q:"The thyroid gland receives sympathetic supply mainly from the:",o:["Facial nerve","Superior cervical ganglion","Vagus nerve","Hypoglossal nerve","Phrenic nerve"],a:1,e:"The thyroid gland receives sympathetic fibers primarily from superior cervical ganglion. Vasomotor changes develop clinically through autonomic influence on thyroid vessels.<br><br>Postganglionic sympathetic fibers travel along thyroid arteries to reach the glandular tissue.<br><br>Facial nerve (option A), vagus nerve (option C), hypoglossal nerve (option D), and phrenic nerve (option E) do not provide sympathetic supply.<br><br><em>(Snell's Clinical Anatomy)</em>"},
  {q:"The follicular cells of thyroid synthesize hormone using:",o:["Calcium","Magnesium","Iodine","Iron","Zinc"],a:2,e:"Iodine is essential for synthesis of thyroxine and triiodothyronine within thyroid follicles. Goiter develops clinically in prolonged iodine deficiency states.<br><br>Thyroid follicular cells actively concentrate iodine from circulation for hormone production.<br><br>Calcium (option A), magnesium (option B), iron (option D), and zinc (option E) are less directly involved in hormone synthesis.<br><br><em>(Guyton and Hall Physiology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient undergoing thyroidectomy develops postoperative tetany. The most likely cause is accidental removal of:",o:["Cervical lymph nodes","Recurrent laryngeal nerve","Parathyroid glands","Cricothyroid muscle","Thyroid isthmus"],a:2,e:"Post-thyroidectomy tetany commonly results from accidental removal or devascularization of parathyroid glands. Perioral numbness develops clinically early in hypocalcemia.<br><br>Parathyroid hormone deficiency reduces serum calcium concentration and increases neuromuscular excitability.<br><br>Cervical lymph nodes (option A), recurrent laryngeal nerve (option B), cricothyroid muscle (option D), and thyroid isthmus (option E) do not cause tetany directly.<br><br><em>(Recall and Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"The thyroid gland is supplied mainly by how many arteries?",o:["One","Two","Three","Four","Five"],a:3,e:"The thyroid gland usually receives blood supply from paired superior and inferior thyroid arteries. Significant vascularity develops clinically as troublesome intraoperative bleeding.<br><br>Occasionally, an additional thyroidea ima artery may contribute to supply.<br><br>One artery (option A), two arteries (option B), three arteries (option C), and five arteries (option E) are incorrect standard descriptions.<br><br><em>(Snell's Clinical Anatomy)</em>"},
  {q:"The ligament attaching thyroid gland to cricoid cartilage is called:",o:["Suspensory ligament of Berry","Cricothyroid ligament","Stylomandibular ligament","Thyrohyoid ligament","Annular ligament"],a:0,e:"Berry ligament firmly anchors thyroid gland to cricoid cartilage and upper trachea. Thyroid swelling therefore moves clinically during swallowing examination.<br><br>The recurrent laryngeal nerve lies very close to this ligament during thyroid surgery.<br><br>Cricothyroid ligament (option B), stylomandibular ligament (option C), thyrohyoid ligament (option D), and annular ligament (option E) are unrelated structures.<br><br><em>(Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"Triiodothyronine is physiologically more active than thyroxine because it:",o:["Contains less iodine","Has longer half-life","Binds poorly to receptors","Has greater metabolic potency","Is produced outside thyroid only"],a:3,e:"Triiodothyronine possesses greater metabolic potency than thyroxine at tissue receptor level. Weight loss and tachycardia develop clinically in excessive hormone states.<br><br>Although produced in smaller quantities, T3 acts more rapidly and strongly on target tissues.<br><br>Less iodine content (option A), longer half-life (option B), poor receptor binding (option C), and exclusive peripheral production (option E) are incorrect explanations.<br><br><em>(Guyton and Hall Physiology)</em>"},
  {q:"A swelling arising from thyroid gland is differentiated from thyroglossal cyst because it:",o:["Does not move on swallowing","Moves with tongue protrusion","Moves only during respiration","Does not move with tongue protrusion","Lies in posterior triangle"],a:3,e:"Thyroid swellings move with swallowing but usually not with tongue protrusion. Clinical differentiation becomes important during neck examination.<br><br>Thyroglossal cysts remain attached to foramen cecum through thyroglossal tract and therefore move during tongue protrusion.<br><br>Failure to move on swallowing (option A), movement with tongue protrusion (option B), respiratory movement only (option C), and posterior triangle location (option E) are incorrect.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"The venous drainage of thyroid gland ultimately reaches the:",o:["Internal jugular and brachiocephalic veins","Portal vein","Pulmonary veins","Azygos vein only","Vertebral venous plexus only"],a:0,e:"The superior and middle thyroid veins drain into internal jugular vein, while inferior thyroid veins drain into brachiocephalic veins. Bleeding develops clinically during thyroid surgery if venous control becomes inadequate.<br><br>Thyroid veins form a rich plexus over gland surface before entering major cervical veins.<br><br>Pulmonary veins (option C), portal vein (option B), azygos vein only (option D), and vertebral plexus only (option E) are incorrect pathways.<br><br><em>(Snell's Clinical Anatomy)</em>"},
  {q:"During thyroidectomy, the recurrent laryngeal nerve is most vulnerable at the point where it:",o:["Enters larynx behind cricothyroid joint","Pierces thyrohyoid membrane","Crosses superior thyroid artery","Passes superficial to carotid sheath","Emerges from vagus at skull base"],a:0,e:"The recurrent laryngeal nerve is especially vulnerable near Berry ligament before entering larynx behind cricothyroid joint. Hoarseness develops clinically after unilateral injury.<br><br>Dense fascial attachment and intimate relation with thyroid capsule make surgical dissection difficult in this region.<br><br>Superior thyroid artery crossing (option C), thyrohyoid membrane entry (option B), carotid sheath relation (option D), and skull base origin (option E) are incorrect.<br><br><em>(Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient develops severe postoperative hemorrhage after thyroid surgery causing respiratory distress. The immediate life-saving step is:",o:["Start thyroxine infusion","Remove skin sutures immediately","Perform indirect laryngoscopy","Give intravenous calcium","Obtain urgent CT scan"],a:1,e:"Post-thyroidectomy hematoma can rapidly compress airway and produce fatal respiratory obstruction. Neck swelling and stridor develop clinically within hours after surgery.<br><br>Immediate opening of wound by removing sutures decompresses the hematoma before definitive hemostasis is performed.<br><br>Thyroxine infusion (option A), indirect laryngoscopy (option C), intravenous calcium (option D), and CT scan (option E) delay emergency airway relief.<br><br><em>(Recall and Scott-Brown's Otorhinolaryngology)</em>"},
  {q:"The ultimobranchial body contributes embryologically to formation of:",o:["Follicular cells","Thyroglossal duct","Thyroid capsule","Parafollicular C cells","Inferior thyroid artery"],a:3,e:"The ultimobranchial body contributes parafollicular C cells to thyroid gland development. Medullary thyroid carcinoma develops clinically from these neuroendocrine cells.<br><br>These cells produce calcitonin and originate embryologically from neural crest-associated tissue.<br><br>Follicular cells (option A), thyroglossal duct (option B), thyroid capsule (option C), and inferior thyroid artery (option E) have different embryological origins.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"A large retrosternal goiter most commonly produces pressure symptoms due to compression of the:",o:["Thoracic duct","Sympathetic chain","Vertebral artery","Esophagus only","Trachea"],a:4,e:"Retrosternal goiter commonly compresses trachea because of limited thoracic inlet space. Inspiratory stridor and dyspnea develop clinically in advanced enlargement.<br><br>The trachea lies directly posterior to thyroid gland and becomes narrowed by progressive gland expansion.<br><br>Thoracic duct (option A), sympathetic chain (option B), vertebral artery (option C), and esophagus only (option D) are less commonly compressed first.<br><br><em>(Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"The inferior thyroid artery usually arises from the:",o:["External carotid artery","Internal carotid artery","Thyrocervical trunk","Costocervical trunk","Common carotid artery"],a:2,e:"The inferior thyroid artery typically arises from thyrocervical trunk, a branch of subclavian artery. Significant bleeding develops clinically if vessel ligation becomes inadequate during surgery.<br><br>Its close relation with recurrent laryngeal nerve makes lower pole dissection particularly important surgically.<br><br>External carotid artery (option A), internal carotid artery (option B), costocervical trunk (option D), and common carotid artery (option E) are incorrect origins.<br><br><em>(Snell's Clinical Anatomy)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with bilateral recurrent laryngeal nerve palsy after thyroidectomy will most likely present with:",o:["Aphonia without dyspnea","Stridor with relatively preserved voice","Nasal regurgitation only","Complete inability to swallow","Deviation of tongue"],a:1,e:"Bilateral recurrent laryngeal nerve paralysis fixes vocal cords near midline, causing airway compromise. Inspiratory stridor develops clinically more prominently than severe voice loss.<br><br>Because cords remain close together, phonation may be relatively preserved despite critical airway narrowing.<br><br>Aphonia without dyspnea (option A), nasal regurgitation (option C), inability to swallow (option D), and tongue deviation (option E) are less typical.<br><br><em>(Scott-Brown's Otorhinolaryngology)</em>"},
  {q:"The blood supply of parathyroid glands is derived mainly from the:",o:["Superior thyroid artery","Lingual artery","Facial artery","Ascending pharyngeal artery","Inferior thyroid artery"],a:4,e:"Parathyroid glands receive principal blood supply from inferior thyroid artery branches. Hypocalcemia develops clinically if vascular supply is compromised during surgery.<br><br>Preservation of these delicate vessels is essential to prevent postoperative hypoparathyroidism and tetany.<br><br>Superior thyroid artery (option A), lingual artery (option B), facial artery (option C), and ascending pharyngeal artery (option D) contribute minimally.<br><br><em>(Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"A thyroid swelling extending behind sternum but not palpable below from neck examination is characteristic of:",o:["Thyroglossal cyst","Toxic adenoma","Lingual thyroid","Retrosternal goiter","Branchial cyst"],a:3,e:"Retrosternal goiter extends into mediastinum and may not be palpable inferiorly during examination. Dyspnea and venous congestion develop clinically in large lesions.<br><br>The enlarged gland descends along fascial planes into thoracic cavity because of negative intrathoracic pressure.<br><br>Thyroglossal cyst (option A), toxic adenoma (option B), lingual thyroid (option C), and branchial cyst (option E) do not show this feature.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"The ligament of Berry is clinically important because it is closely related to the:",o:["Recurrent laryngeal nerve","Hypoglossal nerve","External laryngeal nerve","Superior thyroid vein","Internal jugular vein"],a:0,e:"Berry ligament is closely related to recurrent laryngeal nerve near laryngeal entry point. Hoarseness develops clinically after injury during difficult thyroid dissection.<br><br>Dense attachment between thyroid capsule and cricoid cartilage increases surgical vulnerability of the nerve.<br><br>External laryngeal nerve (option C), hypoglossal nerve (option B), superior thyroid vein (option D), and internal jugular vein (option E) are less closely related.<br><br><em>(Snell's Clinical Anatomy)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with thyroid enlargement develops Pemberton sign. This indicates compression at the:",o:["Carotid bifurcation","Jugular foramen","Thoracic inlet","Cricothyroid membrane","Retropharyngeal space"],a:2,e:"Pemberton sign occurs when raising both arms produces facial congestion and respiratory distress. Venous obstruction develops clinically because of thoracic inlet compression.<br><br>Large retrosternal goiters compress major veins at superior mediastinum during arm elevation.<br><br>Carotid bifurcation (option A), jugular foramen (option B), cricothyroid membrane (option D), and retropharyngeal space (option E) are unrelated sites.<br><br><em>(Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"The most common malignant tumor of thyroid gland is:",o:["Follicular carcinoma","Medullary carcinoma","Papillary carcinoma","Anaplastic carcinoma","Lymphoma"],a:2,e:"Papillary carcinoma is the commonest malignant tumor of thyroid gland. Cervical lymph node metastasis develops clinically early despite relatively favorable long-term prognosis.<br><br>The tumor commonly affects younger adults and spreads predominantly through lymphatic channels within the neck.<br><br>Follicular carcinoma (option A), medullary carcinoma (option B), anaplastic carcinoma (option D), and lymphoma (option E) are less common thyroid malignancies.<br><br><em>(Recall and Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"The thyroid carcinoma most strongly associated with previous radiation exposure is:",o:["Medullary carcinoma","Papillary carcinoma","Anaplastic carcinoma","Follicular carcinoma","Hurthle cell carcinoma"],a:1,e:"Papillary carcinoma shows a strong association with childhood neck irradiation exposure. Painless thyroid swelling develops clinically years after radiation contact.<br><br>Ionizing radiation induces genetic mutations that predispose thyroid follicular epithelium to malignant transformation.<br><br>Medullary carcinoma (option A), anaplastic carcinoma (option C), follicular carcinoma (option D), and Hurthle cell carcinoma (option E) are less strongly linked.<br><br><em>(Scott-Brown's Otorhinolaryngology)</em>"},
  {q:"Follicular carcinoma of thyroid commonly spreads through:",o:["Lymphatics","Direct implantation","Perineural invasion","Bloodstream","CSF pathways"],a:3,e:"Follicular thyroid carcinoma characteristically spreads hematogenously rather than through lymphatics. Bone and lung metastases develop clinically in advanced disease.<br><br>The tumor invades blood vessels microscopically, allowing distant dissemination through systemic circulation.<br><br>Lymphatic spread (option A), direct implantation (option B), perineural invasion (option C), and CSF dissemination (option E) are less typical.<br><br><em>(Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with thyroid malignancy develops diarrhea and flushing. The most likely diagnosis is:",o:["Papillary carcinoma","Follicular carcinoma","Anaplastic carcinoma","Thyroid lymphoma","Medullary carcinoma"],a:4,e:"Medullary carcinoma arises from parafollicular C cells and may produce calcitonin-related systemic symptoms. Flushing and diarrhea develop clinically due to hormone secretion.<br><br>This neuroendocrine tumor may occur sporadically or as part of MEN syndromes.<br><br>Papillary carcinoma (option A), follicular carcinoma (option B), anaplastic carcinoma (option C), and lymphoma (option D) lack these secretory manifestations.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"The thyroid malignancy with worst prognosis is:",o:["Papillary carcinoma","Follicular carcinoma","Medullary carcinoma","Hurthle cell carcinoma","Anaplastic carcinoma"],a:4,e:"Anaplastic carcinoma carries the worst prognosis among thyroid malignancies. Rapidly enlarging neck mass and airway compromise develop clinically within short duration.<br><br>The tumor is highly aggressive, locally invasive, and usually presents in elderly patients with advanced disease.<br><br>Papillary carcinoma (option A), follicular carcinoma (option B), medullary carcinoma (option C), and Hurthle cell carcinoma (option D) progress less aggressively.<br><br><em>(Scott-Brown's Otorhinolaryngology)</em>"},
  {q:"The most common presentation of papillary thyroid carcinoma is:",o:["Solitary thyroid nodule","Painful thyroid swelling","Hyperthyroidism","Hoarseness alone","Stridor only"],a:0,e:"Papillary thyroid carcinoma commonly presents as a solitary painless thyroid nodule. Cervical lymphadenopathy develops clinically in many patients during evaluation.<br><br>The lesion usually grows slowly and may remain asymptomatic for prolonged periods.<br><br>Hyperthyroidism (option C), painful swelling (option B), isolated hoarseness (option D), and stridor alone (option E) are less typical presentations.<br><br><em>(Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"Psammoma bodies are characteristically seen in:",o:["Follicular carcinoma","Papillary carcinoma","Medullary carcinoma","Anaplastic carcinoma","Thyroid lymphoma"],a:1,e:"Psammoma bodies are concentrically calcified microscopic structures characteristic of papillary thyroid carcinoma. Cervical nodal metastasis develops clinically despite excellent prognosis.<br><br>These laminated calcifications are important histopathological clues supporting papillary differentiation.<br><br>Follicular carcinoma (option A), medullary carcinoma (option C), anaplastic carcinoma (option D), and lymphoma (option E) usually lack psammoma bodies.<br><br><em>(Robbins Basic Pathology)</em>"},
  {q:"A rapidly enlarging hard thyroid mass causing dysphagia in an elderly patient most likely represents:",o:["Papillary carcinoma","Follicular adenoma","Colloid goiter","Anaplastic carcinoma","Thyroglossal cyst"],a:3,e:"Anaplastic thyroid carcinoma commonly presents as rapidly enlarging hard neck mass in elderly individuals. Dysphagia and airway compromise develop clinically early because of local invasion.<br><br>The tumor infiltrates surrounding tissues aggressively and carries extremely poor prognosis.<br><br>Papillary carcinoma (option A), follicular adenoma (option B), colloid goiter (option C), and thyroglossal cyst (option E) progress more slowly.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"The investigation most useful for initial evaluation of thyroid nodule is:",o:["FNAC","Plain neck X-ray","PET scan","Sialography","Barium swallow"],a:0,e:"FNAC is the investigation of choice for evaluating thyroid nodules initially. Malignancy suspicion develops clinically in hard or fixed thyroid lesions.<br><br>The procedure is minimally invasive and provides valuable cytological diagnosis before definitive surgery.<br><br>Plain neck X-ray (option B), PET scan (option C), sialography (option D), and barium swallow (option E) are less appropriate initial tests.<br><br><em>(Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"Medullary carcinoma of thyroid originates from:",o:["Parafollicular C cells","Thyroglossal duct remnants","Follicular cells","Thyroid capsule","Hurthle cells"],a:0,e:"Medullary thyroid carcinoma originates from parafollicular C cells of neural crest origin. Elevated calcitonin levels develop clinically in affected patients.<br><br>These cells normally participate in calcium regulation through calcitonin secretion.<br><br>Follicular cells (option C), thyroglossal remnants (option B), thyroid capsule (option D), and Hurthle cells (option E) are unrelated origins.<br><br><em>(Scott-Brown's Otorhinolaryngology)</em>"},
  {q:"The thyroid carcinoma most likely to metastasize to bone is:",o:["Papillary carcinoma","Papillary microcarcinoma","Medullary carcinoma","Thyroid lymphoma","Follicular carcinoma"],a:4,e:"Follicular thyroid carcinoma commonly metastasizes hematogenously to bone and lungs. Pathological fractures develop clinically in advanced skeletal involvement.<br><br>Vascular invasion is an important microscopic feature distinguishing follicular carcinoma from adenoma.<br><br>Papillary carcinoma (option A), medullary carcinoma (option C), thyroid lymphoma (option D), and papillary microcarcinoma (option B) less commonly involve bone.<br><br><em>(Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"A thyroid malignancy associated with MEN 2 syndrome is:",o:["Papillary carcinoma","Follicular carcinoma","Hurthle cell carcinoma","Medullary carcinoma","Anaplastic carcinoma"],a:3,e:"Medullary thyroid carcinoma is strongly associated with MEN 2 syndromes and RET proto-oncogene mutations. Bilateral disease develops clinically in hereditary forms.<br><br>Screening family members becomes important because of autosomal dominant inheritance patterns.<br><br>Papillary carcinoma (option A), follicular carcinoma (option B), Hurthle cell carcinoma (option C), and anaplastic carcinoma (option E) lack this association.<br><br><em>(Recall and Robbins Basic Pathology)</em>"},
  {q:"Orphan Annie eye nuclei are characteristic of:",o:["Medullary carcinoma","Follicular carcinoma","Papillary carcinoma","Anaplastic carcinoma","Thyroid lymphoma"],a:2,e:"Orphan Annie eye nuclei are characteristic nuclear features of papillary thyroid carcinoma. Cervical nodal metastasis develops clinically despite generally excellent survival rates.<br><br>The nuclei appear optically clear because of dispersed chromatin distribution within tumor cells.<br><br>Medullary carcinoma (option A), follicular carcinoma (option B), anaplastic carcinoma (option D), and lymphoma (option E) do not show this feature.<br><br><em>(Robbins Basic Pathology)</em>"},
  {q:"The tumor marker used for follow-up of medullary thyroid carcinoma is:",o:["Calcitonin","TSH","Thyroglobulin","T3","T4"],a:0,e:"Calcitonin serves as an important tumor marker for medullary thyroid carcinoma follow-up. Persistent elevation develops clinically in recurrent or metastatic disease.<br><br>The hormone is produced by parafollicular C cells from which this tumor originates.<br><br>Thyroglobulin (option C), TSH (option B), T3 (option D), and T4 (option E) are less useful markers here.<br><br><em>(Scott-Brown's Otorhinolaryngology)</em>"},
  {q:"A fixed hard thyroid swelling with recurrent laryngeal nerve palsy most strongly suggests:",o:["Benign colloid goiter","Graves disease","Thyroglossal cyst","Follicular adenoma","Thyroid carcinoma"],a:4,e:"Hard fixed thyroid swelling associated with recurrent laryngeal nerve palsy strongly suggests malignant infiltration. Hoarseness develops clinically due to vocal cord paralysis.<br><br>Local invasion beyond thyroid capsule is an important sign of advanced thyroid malignancy.<br><br>Benign colloid goiter (option A), Graves disease (option B), thyroglossal cyst (option C), and follicular adenoma (option D) rarely cause nerve palsy.<br><br><em>(Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"The commonest thyroid malignancy in children is:",o:["Medullary carcinoma","Follicular carcinoma","Papillary carcinoma","Anaplastic carcinoma","Thyroid lymphoma"],a:2,e:"Papillary carcinoma is the commonest thyroid malignancy in children and adolescents. Cervical lymph node metastasis develops clinically more frequently than in adults.<br><br>Despite nodal involvement, long-term prognosis remains excellent with appropriate management.<br><br>Medullary carcinoma (option A), follicular carcinoma (option B), anaplastic carcinoma (option D), and lymphoma (option E) are less common in childhood.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"Amyloid stroma is a histological feature of:",o:["Medullary carcinoma","Follicular carcinoma","Papillary carcinoma","Anaplastic carcinoma","Hurthle cell adenoma"],a:0,e:"Amyloid deposition within tumor stroma is characteristic of medullary thyroid carcinoma. Diarrhea and flushing develop clinically in functioning tumors.<br><br>The amyloid derives from altered calcitonin molecules secreted by neoplastic parafollicular cells.<br><br>Papillary carcinoma (option C), follicular carcinoma (option B), anaplastic carcinoma (option D), and Hurthle cell adenoma (option E) lack amyloid stroma.<br><br><em>(Robbins Basic Pathology)</em>"},
  {q:"The most common route of spread of papillary thyroid carcinoma is through:",o:["Blood vessels","CSF pathways","Perineural invasion","Lymphatics","Pleural cavity"],a:3,e:"Papillary thyroid carcinoma spreads predominantly through lymphatic channels to cervical lymph nodes. Neck node enlargement develops clinically even with small primary lesions.<br><br>This pattern contrasts with follicular carcinoma, which commonly spreads hematogenously.<br><br>Blood vessels (option A), CSF pathways (option B), perineural invasion (option C), and pleural spread (option E) are less typical.<br><br><em>(Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"The thyroid malignancy most commonly associated with long-standing goiter is:",o:["Papillary carcinoma","Follicular carcinoma","Medullary carcinoma","Thyroid lymphoma","Anaplastic carcinoma"],a:4,e:"Anaplastic thyroid carcinoma frequently develops in elderly patients with longstanding multinodular goiter history. Rapid enlargement and airway compromise develop clinically suddenly.<br><br>Dedifferentiation from preexisting thyroid disease is believed to contribute to tumor development.<br><br>Papillary carcinoma (option A), follicular carcinoma (option B), medullary carcinoma (option C), and lymphoma (option D) show weaker associations.<br><br><em>(Scott-Brown's Otorhinolaryngology)</em>"},
  {q:"The tumor marker commonly used after papillary thyroid carcinoma treatment is:",o:["Calcitonin","Thyroglobulin","TSH receptor antibody","Serum iodine","ACTH"],a:1,e:"Thyroglobulin serves as an important follow-up marker after treatment of differentiated thyroid carcinoma. Rising levels develop clinically in recurrent or metastatic disease.<br><br>After total thyroidectomy and radioiodine ablation, serum thyroglobulin should remain very low or undetectable.<br><br>Calcitonin (option A), TSH receptor antibody (option C), serum iodine (option D), and ACTH (option E) are less appropriate markers.<br><br><em>(Recall and Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"A 34-year-old woman presents with a solitary thyroid nodule and ipsilateral cervical lymphadenopathy. FNAC from the thyroid swelling shows nuclear grooves and psammoma bodies. The most likely diagnosis is:",o:["Papillary carcinoma","Medullary carcinoma","Follicular carcinoma","Anaplastic carcinoma","Thyroid lymphoma"],a:0,e:"Papillary thyroid carcinoma commonly presents with cervical lymph node metastasis despite relatively indolent tumor behavior. Painless thyroid swelling develops clinically in younger adults.<br><br>Nuclear grooves, Orphan Annie nuclei, and psammoma bodies are classic pathological hallmarks of papillary carcinoma.<br><br>Follicular carcinoma (option C), medullary carcinoma (option B), anaplastic carcinoma (option D), and lymphoma (option E) show different histopathological patterns.<br><br><em>(Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"A 65-year-old man develops rapidly enlarging thyroid swelling associated with hoarseness, dysphagia, and stridor over two months. The most likely diagnosis is:",o:["Papillary carcinoma","Follicular adenoma","Medullary carcinoma","Anaplastic carcinoma","Graves disease"],a:3,e:"Anaplastic carcinoma presents as rapidly enlarging invasive thyroid mass in elderly patients. Airway obstruction and recurrent laryngeal nerve palsy develop clinically early.<br><br>The tumor demonstrates highly aggressive local infiltration with extremely poor prognosis despite treatment.<br><br>Papillary carcinoma (option A), follicular adenoma (option B), medullary carcinoma (option C), and Graves disease (option E) usually progress more slowly.<br><br><em>(Scott-Brown's Otorhinolaryngology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with medullary thyroid carcinoma should be screened preoperatively for:",o:["Diabetes mellitus","Pheochromocytoma","Tuberculosis","Hyperparathyroidism only","Acromegaly"],a:1,e:"Medullary thyroid carcinoma may occur as part of MEN 2 syndrome associated with pheochromocytoma. Hypertensive crises develop clinically during surgery if adrenal tumors remain undiagnosed.<br><br>Screening with catecholamine studies becomes essential before definitive thyroid surgery.<br><br>Diabetes mellitus (option A), tuberculosis (option C), isolated hyperparathyroidism (option D), and acromegaly (option E) are less critical associations.<br><br><em>(Robbins Basic Pathology)</em>"},
  {q:"A 48-year-old woman has thyroid swelling with distant bone metastases but minimal cervical nodal enlargement. The most likely diagnosis is:",o:["Papillary carcinoma","Medullary carcinoma","Follicular carcinoma","Anaplastic carcinoma","Thyroid lymphoma"],a:2,e:"Follicular carcinoma commonly spreads hematogenously to bone and lungs rather than through cervical lymphatics. Bone pain develops clinically in metastatic disease.<br><br>Vascular invasion is the major pathological feature responsible for bloodstream dissemination.<br><br>Papillary carcinoma (option A), medullary carcinoma (option B), anaplastic carcinoma (option D), and lymphoma (option E) less commonly show this pattern.<br><br><em>(Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"A 29-year-old woman treated previously with childhood neck irradiation develops a painless thyroid nodule. The most likely malignancy is:",o:["Medullary carcinoma","Follicular carcinoma","Thyroid lymphoma","Hurthle cell carcinoma","Papillary carcinoma"],a:4,e:"Papillary thyroid carcinoma shows strong association with previous ionizing radiation exposure during childhood. Cervical nodal metastasis develops clinically despite favorable prognosis.<br><br>Radiation-induced mutations promote malignant transformation of thyroid follicular epithelium over several years.<br><br>Medullary carcinoma (option A), follicular carcinoma (option B), lymphoma (option C), and Hurthle cell carcinoma (option D) show weaker associations.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient undergoes total thyroidectomy for papillary carcinoma. During follow-up, rising serum thyroglobulin levels most strongly suggest:",o:["Residual or recurrent disease","Hyperparathyroidism","Hypocalcemia","Pituitary adenoma","Medullary transformation"],a:0,e:"Thyroglobulin serves as an important tumor marker after treatment of differentiated thyroid carcinoma. Rising levels develop clinically with recurrent or metastatic disease.<br><br>After complete thyroid ablation, serum thyroglobulin should remain undetectable or extremely low.<br><br>Hypocalcemia (option C), hyperparathyroidism (option B), pituitary adenoma (option D), and medullary transformation (option E) do not elevate thyroglobulin significantly.<br><br><em>(Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"A 70-year-old woman develops rapidly progressive thyroid enlargement with pressure symptoms. Biopsy reveals giant cells and marked pleomorphism. The diagnosis is:",o:["Medullary carcinoma","Follicular carcinoma","Papillary carcinoma","Thyroid lymphoma","Anaplastic carcinoma"],a:4,e:"Anaplastic thyroid carcinoma demonstrates giant cells, pleomorphism, and highly undifferentiated histology. Dysphagia and airway compromise develop clinically within weeks or months.<br><br>The disease usually presents late with extensive local invasion and dismal survival rates.<br><br>Medullary carcinoma (option A), follicular carcinoma (option B), papillary carcinoma (option C), and lymphoma (option D) have different microscopic appearances.<br><br><em>(Robbins Basic Pathology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with thyroid malignancy develops persistent diarrhea, flushing, and elevated calcitonin levels. The tumor originates from:",o:["Follicular epithelium","Thyroglossal duct remnants","Hurthle cells","Parafollicular C cells","Thyroid capsule"],a:3,e:"Medullary thyroid carcinoma arises from parafollicular C cells responsible for calcitonin secretion. Secretory symptoms develop clinically in hormonally active tumors.<br><br>The tumor may occur sporadically or in association with inherited MEN syndromes.<br><br>Follicular epithelium (option A), thyroglossal remnants (option B), Hurthle cells (option C), and thyroid capsule (option E) are unrelated origins.<br><br><em>(Scott-Brown's Otorhinolaryngology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient presents with hard fixed thyroid swelling, hoarseness, and ipsilateral vocal cord paralysis. Which feature most strongly indicates malignancy?",o:["Movement with swallowing","Female gender","Solitary thyroid nodule","Vocal cord paralysis","Presence of colloid"],a:3,e:"Vocal cord paralysis in thyroid swelling strongly suggests recurrent laryngeal nerve infiltration by malignancy. Hoarseness develops clinically due to impaired cord mobility.<br><br>Benign thyroid lesions rarely invade adjacent neural structures or produce fixation of vocal cords.<br><br>Movement with swallowing (option A), female gender (option B), solitary nodule (option C), and colloid presence (option E) are less specific indicators.<br><br><em>(Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"A thyroid tumor demonstrates amyloid stroma on histopathology and positive family history of endocrine neoplasia. The diagnosis is:",o:["Papillary carcinoma","Follicular carcinoma","Anaplastic carcinoma","Thyroid lymphoma","Medullary carcinoma"],a:4,e:"Amyloid stroma is a characteristic pathological feature of medullary thyroid carcinoma. Familial cases develop clinically in association with MEN 2 syndromes.<br><br>The amyloid material derives from altered calcitonin molecules secreted by neoplastic C cells.<br><br>Papillary carcinoma (option A), follicular carcinoma (option B), anaplastic carcinoma (option C), and lymphoma (option D) do not produce amyloid stroma.<br><br><em>(Robbins Basic Pathology)</em>"},
  {q:"A 32-year-old woman presents with diffuse thyroid enlargement, weight loss, heat intolerance, and bilateral exophthalmos. The most likely diagnosis is:",o:["Hashimoto thyroiditis","Graves disease","Multinodular goiter","De Quervain thyroiditis","Follicular adenoma"],a:1,e:"Graves disease is an autoimmune hyperthyroid disorder characterized by diffuse toxic goiter and ophthalmopathy. Tachycardia and tremors develop clinically because of excessive thyroid hormone production.<br><br>TSH receptor-stimulating antibodies produce diffuse gland hyperplasia and increased hormone synthesis.<br><br>Hashimoto thyroiditis (option A), multinodular goiter (option C), De Quervain thyroiditis (option D), and follicular adenoma (option E) present differently.<br><br><em>(Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"The most common cause of hypothyroidism in iodine-sufficient regions is:",o:["Hashimoto thyroiditis","Follicular adenoma","Graves disease","Toxic multinodular goiter","De Quervain thyroiditis"],a:0,e:"Hashimoto thyroiditis is the commonest cause of hypothyroidism in iodine-sufficient populations. Fatigue and weight gain develop clinically because of reduced thyroid hormone levels.<br><br>The disease results from autoimmune destruction of thyroid follicular tissue with lymphocytic infiltration.<br><br>Graves disease (option C), follicular adenoma (option B), toxic multinodular goiter (option D), and De Quervain thyroiditis (option E) are less common causes.<br><br><em>(Robbins Basic Pathology)</em>"},
  {q:"A 45-year-old woman presents with painful tender thyroid swelling following viral upper respiratory infection. ESR is markedly elevated. The diagnosis is:",o:["Graves disease","Hashimoto thyroiditis","Follicular carcinoma","De Quervain thyroiditis","Thyroid lymphoma"],a:3,e:"De Quervain thyroiditis is a painful granulomatous thyroid inflammation commonly following viral infection. Fever and neck tenderness develop clinically prominently.<br><br>Raised ESR and transient thyrotoxicosis are important laboratory features during acute inflammatory phase.<br><br>Graves disease (option A), Hashimoto thyroiditis (option B), follicular carcinoma (option C), and lymphoma (option E) are less painful conditions.<br><br><em>(Recall and Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"The most common cause of diffuse euthyroid goiter worldwide is:",o:["Radiation exposure","Autoimmune disease","Iodine deficiency","Thyroid adenoma","Pituitary tumor"],a:2,e:"Iodine deficiency remains the most common cause of diffuse endemic goiter worldwide. Neck swelling develops clinically because of compensatory thyroid hyperplasia.<br><br>Reduced thyroid hormone synthesis stimulates increased TSH secretion and gland enlargement.<br><br>Radiation exposure (option A), autoimmune disease (option B), thyroid adenoma (option D), and pituitary tumor (option E) are less common causes globally.<br><br><em>(Guyton and Hall Physiology)</em>"},
  {q:"A 38-year-old woman develops recurrent laryngeal nerve palsy after subtotal thyroidectomy. The patient will most likely present with:",o:["Hoarseness","Nasal regurgitation","Dysphagia only","Hemoptysis","Facial asymmetry"],a:0,e:"Recurrent laryngeal nerve injury commonly produces hoarseness after thyroid surgery. Voice weakness develops clinically because of ipsilateral vocal cord paralysis.<br><br>The nerve supplies all intrinsic laryngeal muscles except cricothyroid muscle.<br><br>Dysphagia alone (option C), nasal regurgitation (option B), hemoptysis (option D), and facial asymmetry (option E) are less characteristic findings.<br><br><em>(Scott-Brown's Otorhinolaryngology)</em>"},
  {q:"The investigation most useful for differentiating solid from cystic thyroid swelling is:",o:["PET scan","Plain neck X-ray","Ultrasonography","Sialography","Barium swallow"],a:2,e:"Ultrasonography is the preferred initial imaging modality for thyroid nodules and swellings. Cystic degeneration develops clinically in longstanding nodular lesions.<br><br>The investigation accurately differentiates cystic, solid, and mixed thyroid pathology without radiation exposure.<br><br>PET scan (option A), plain X-ray (option B), sialography (option D), and barium swallow (option E) are less useful initially.<br><br><em>(Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with multinodular goiter develops sudden painful enlargement of thyroid swelling. The most likely cause is:",o:["Hyperplasia","Malignant transformation","Amyloidosis","Graves disease","Hemorrhage into cyst"],a:4,e:"Sudden painful enlargement in multinodular goiter commonly results from hemorrhage into a thyroid cyst. Pressure symptoms develop clinically because of rapid expansion.<br><br>Degenerative cystic areas within nodules are prone to spontaneous bleeding.<br><br>Hyperplasia (option A), malignant transformation (option B), Graves disease (option D), and amyloidosis (option C) are less abrupt causes.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"A 29-year-old woman presents with diffuse toxic goiter and severe ophthalmopathy. The underlying mechanism is:",o:["Bacterial infection","Autoimmune stimulation of TSH receptors","Excess iodine intake only","Hematogenous spread","Pituitary infarction"],a:1,e:"Graves disease results from IgG antibodies stimulating TSH receptors on thyroid follicular cells. Exophthalmos develops clinically because of autoimmune orbital inflammation.<br><br>This stimulation causes diffuse gland hyperplasia with excessive thyroid hormone production.<br><br>Bacterial infection (option A), excess iodine alone (option C), hematogenous spread (option D), and pituitary infarction (option E) are incorrect mechanisms.<br><br><em>(Robbins Basic Pathology)</em>"},
  {q:"The most common complication immediately after thyroidectomy is:",o:["Thyroid storm","Hypocalcemia","Tracheomalacia","Hypothyroidism","Hemorrhage"],a:4,e:"Post-thyroidectomy hemorrhage is an important early surgical complication that may rapidly compromise airway. Neck swelling and respiratory distress develop clinically urgently.<br><br>Prompt wound decompression and hemostasis are essential life-saving measures.<br><br>Thyroid storm (option A), hypocalcemia (option B), hypothyroidism (option D), and tracheomalacia (option C) usually occur later or less frequently.<br><br><em>(Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with long-standing multinodular goiter develops thyrotoxicosis without ophthalmopathy. The diagnosis is:",o:["Graves disease","Toxic multinodular goiter","Hashimoto thyroiditis","De Quervain thyroiditis","Thyroid lymphoma"],a:1,e:"Toxic multinodular goiter causes hyperthyroidism because autonomously functioning nodules secrete excess thyroid hormone. Palpitations develop clinically in elderly patients commonly.<br><br>Unlike Graves disease, ophthalmopathy and diffuse gland involvement are usually absent.<br><br>Graves disease (option A), Hashimoto thyroiditis (option C), De Quervain thyroiditis (option D), and lymphoma (option E) differ clinically.<br><br><em>(Scott-Brown's Otorhinolaryngology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient develops circumoral numbness and carpopedal spasm after thyroid surgery. The likely cause is:",o:["Recurrent laryngeal nerve injury","Hyperkalemia","Hypocalcemia","Hyperthyroidism","Vagal injury"],a:2,e:"Hypocalcemia after thyroid surgery usually results from accidental parathyroid removal or devascularization. Tetany develops clinically with neuromuscular irritability and muscle spasms.<br><br>Serum calcium reduction increases neuronal excitability producing characteristic signs and symptoms.<br><br>Recurrent laryngeal nerve injury (option A), hyperkalemia (option B), hyperthyroidism (option D), and vagal injury (option E) do not explain tetany.<br><br><em>(Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"The most common benign neoplasm of thyroid gland is:",o:["Papillary carcinoma","Medullary carcinoma","Anaplastic carcinoma","Thyroid lymphoma","Follicular adenoma"],a:4,e:"Follicular adenoma is the commonest benign thyroid neoplasm. Solitary painless thyroid nodule develops clinically in middle-aged adults.<br><br>The lesion remains encapsulated and lacks vascular or capsular invasion seen in follicular carcinoma.<br><br>Papillary carcinoma (option A), medullary carcinoma (option B), thyroid lymphoma (option D), and anaplastic carcinoma (option C) are malignant tumors.<br><br><em>(Robbins Basic Pathology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with Graves disease is most likely to show:",o:["Bradycardia","Cold intolerance","Weight gain","Pretibial myxedema","Delayed reflexes"],a:3,e:"Pretibial myxedema is a characteristic extrathyroidal manifestation of Graves disease. Heat intolerance and tremors develop clinically because of excessive thyroid hormone activity.<br><br>The condition results from autoimmune glycosaminoglycan deposition within dermis and subcutaneous tissues.<br><br>Bradycardia (option A), cold intolerance (option B), weight gain (option C), and delayed reflexes (option E) suggest hypothyroidism instead.<br><br><em>(Guyton and Hall Physiology)</em>"},
  {q:"A thyroid swelling moving with deglutition but not with tongue protrusion most likely arises from:",o:["Thyroglossal cyst","Lingual thyroid","Thyroid gland","Dermoid cyst","Branchial cyst"],a:2,e:"Thyroid swellings characteristically move with swallowing because of attachment to larynx and trachea. Neck mass elevation develops clinically during deglutition examination.<br><br>Unlike thyroglossal cysts, thyroid swellings usually do not move with tongue protrusion.<br><br>Thyroglossal cyst (option A), lingual thyroid (option B), dermoid cyst (option D), and branchial cyst (option E) behave differently.<br><br><em>(Recall and Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient develops thyroid storm after surgery. The most important initial management step is:",o:["Immediate radioiodine therapy","Observation only","FNAC of thyroid gland","Total thyroidectomy","Intravenous propranolol and supportive care"],a:4,e:"Thyroid storm is a life-threatening hypermetabolic emergency occurring in uncontrolled thyrotoxicosis. Hyperpyrexia and tachyarrhythmias develop clinically rapidly after stress or surgery.<br><br>Immediate stabilization with beta-blockers, fluids, cooling, and antithyroid measures becomes essential.<br><br>Radioiodine therapy (option A), FNAC (option C), thyroidectomy (option D), and observation (option B) are inappropriate emergency responses.<br><br><em>(Scott-Brown's Otorhinolaryngology)</em>"},
  {q:"A middle-aged woman presents with painless diffuse thyroid enlargement and hypothyroidism. Anti-thyroid peroxidase antibodies are strongly positive. The diagnosis is:",o:["Graves disease","De Quervain thyroiditis","Hashimoto thyroiditis","Toxic adenoma","Thyroid lymphoma"],a:2,e:"Hashimoto thyroiditis is an autoimmune disorder characterized by lymphocytic thyroid destruction and hypothyroidism. Fatigue and cold intolerance develop clinically progressively.<br><br>Anti-thyroid peroxidase antibodies are important serological markers supporting diagnosis.<br><br>Graves disease (option A), De Quervain thyroiditis (option B), toxic adenoma (option D), and lymphoma (option E) present differently.<br><br><em>(Robbins Basic Pathology)</em>"},
  {q:"A 60-year-old woman with long-standing goiter develops inspiratory stridor while lying supine. The most likely explanation is:",o:["Vocal abuse","Tracheal compression","Esophageal rupture","Glossopharyngeal palsy","Acute epiglottitis"],a:1,e:"Large multinodular or retrosternal goiters may compress trachea causing airway narrowing. Inspiratory stridor develops clinically especially in supine position.<br><br>Progressive thyroid enlargement reduces tracheal lumen because of limited cervical and mediastinal space.<br><br>Vocal abuse (option A), esophageal rupture (option C), glossopharyngeal palsy (option D), and epiglottitis (option E) are less likely explanations.<br><br><em>(Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with solitary toxic thyroid nodule is expected to show:",o:["Low radioactive iodine uptake in nodule","Increased uptake confined to nodule","Absent thyroid activity entirely","Uniform diffuse uptake","Elevated serum calcitonin"],a:1,e:"Solitary toxic adenoma demonstrates increased radionuclide uptake within autonomously functioning nodule. Hyperthyroid symptoms develop clinically because of excess hormone secretion.<br><br>Suppression of surrounding normal thyroid tissue commonly accompanies hyperfunctioning nodules.<br><br>Low uptake (option A), absent activity (option C), diffuse uptake (option D), and elevated calcitonin (option E) suggest other disorders.<br><br><em>(Scott-Brown's Otorhinolaryngology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with long-standing Hashimoto thyroiditis has increased risk of developing:",o:["Papillary carcinoma","Medullary carcinoma","Toxic goiter","Follicular adenoma","Thyroid lymphoma"],a:4,e:"Chronic autoimmune thyroiditis predisposes to primary thyroid lymphoma because of prolonged lymphocytic stimulation. Rapid gland enlargement develops clinically in affected patients.<br><br>Most thyroid lymphomas arise from B lymphocytes within chronically inflamed thyroid tissue.<br><br>Papillary carcinoma (option A), medullary carcinoma (option B), follicular adenoma (option D), and toxic goiter (option C) show weaker associations.<br><br><em>(Robbins Basic Pathology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with multinodular goiter develops facial congestion and respiratory distress after raising both arms. This is called:",o:["Trousseau sign","Chvostek sign","Kocher sign","Pemberton sign","Stellwag sign"],a:3,e:"Pemberton sign occurs due to thoracic inlet obstruction from large retrosternal thyroid enlargement. Facial congestion develops clinically when arm elevation further narrows venous drainage.<br><br>The sign indicates significant compressive effect of thyroid swelling within superior mediastinum.<br><br>Trousseau sign (option A), Chvostek sign (option B), Kocher sign (option C), and Stellwag sign (option E) indicate different conditions.<br><br><em>(Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"A 35-year-old woman with Graves disease is planned for subtotal thyroidectomy. Before surgery, the most important objective of preoperative preparation is to make the patient:",o:["Hypocalcemic","Euthyroid","Hypothyroid","Bradycardic only","Hyperglycemic"],a:1,e:"Patients with Graves disease should be rendered euthyroid before thyroid surgery. Tachyarrhythmias and thyroid storm develop clinically if uncontrolled thyrotoxicosis persists perioperatively.<br><br>Antithyroid drugs and beta-blockers are commonly used to achieve metabolic stabilization before surgery.<br><br>Hypocalcemia (option A), hypothyroidism (option C), isolated bradycardia (option D), and hyperglycemia (option E) are not operative goals.<br><br><em>(Recall and Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient develops stridor within six hours after thyroidectomy. The first diagnosis to exclude urgently is:",o:["Tracheomalacia","Pulmonary embolism","Pneumothorax","Vocal abuse","Wound hematoma"],a:4,e:"Post-thyroidectomy hematoma is a surgical emergency because expanding neck swelling may rapidly obstruct airway. Respiratory distress develops clinically within early postoperative hours.<br><br>Immediate wound decompression and evacuation are essential before definitive hemostasis.<br><br>Tracheomalacia (option A), pulmonary embolism (option B), vocal abuse (option D), and pneumothorax (option C) are less immediate causes.<br><br><em>(Scott-Brown's Otorhinolaryngology)</em>"},
  {q:"A 42-year-old woman with multinodular goiter presents with dyspnea on lying flat and positive Pemberton sign. The preferred management is:",o:["Observation only","Oral antibiotics","Radioiodine immediately","Surgical thyroidectomy","Steroid therapy"],a:3,e:"Large multinodular goiters producing compressive symptoms usually require surgical removal. Venous congestion and airway compromise develop clinically in retrosternal extension.<br><br>Positive Pemberton sign suggests thoracic inlet obstruction requiring definitive decompression.<br><br>Observation (option A), antibiotics (option B), immediate radioiodine (option C), and steroids (option E) provide inadequate relief of compression.<br><br><em>(Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with toxic multinodular goiter is elderly and unfit for surgery. The most appropriate definitive treatment is:",o:["FNAC","Radioiodine therapy","Hemithyroidectomy","Chemotherapy","Tracheostomy"],a:1,e:"Radioiodine therapy is commonly preferred in elderly toxic multinodular goiter patients unfit for surgery. Palpitations and weight loss develop clinically due to excess hormone secretion.<br><br>The treatment selectively destroys hyperfunctioning thyroid tissue over time.<br><br>FNAC (option A), hemithyroidectomy (option C), chemotherapy (option D), and tracheostomy (option E) are less appropriate definitive options.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient develops circumoral tingling and carpopedal spasm after total thyroidectomy. The immediate management includes:",o:["Oral thyroxine only","Radioiodine therapy","Intravenous calcium administration","Corticosteroids only","Antithyroid drugs"],a:2,e:"Post-thyroidectomy hypocalcemia results from parathyroid injury or devascularization. Tetany develops clinically with neuromuscular irritability and painful spasms.<br><br>Intravenous calcium rapidly corrects symptomatic hypocalcemia and prevents severe complications.<br><br>Oral thyroxine (option A), radioiodine (option B), corticosteroids (option D), and antithyroid drugs (option E) are not immediate treatments.<br><br><em>(Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with Graves disease continues to have severe thyrotoxicosis despite adequate carbimazole therapy. The most appropriate next management option is:",o:["Observation only","Increase dietary iodine","Repeat FNAC","Radioiodine or surgery","Antibiotics"],a:3,e:"Persistent thyrotoxicosis despite medical therapy requires definitive treatment with surgery or radioiodine. Weight loss and tachycardia develop clinically with uncontrolled disease.<br><br>Choice depends upon age, gland size, ophthalmopathy, and patient suitability.<br><br>Observation (option A), dietary iodine increase (option B), repeat FNAC (option C), and antibiotics (option E) are less effective strategies.<br><br><em>(Scott-Brown's Otorhinolaryngology)</em>"},
  {q:"A woman with Hashimoto thyroiditis presents with fatigue, cold intolerance, and elevated TSH levels. The standard long-term treatment is:",o:["Carbimazole","Radioiodine therapy","Potassium iodide","Total thyroidectomy","Levothyroxine replacement"],a:4,e:"Hashimoto thyroiditis commonly progresses to hypothyroidism requiring lifelong hormone replacement. Fatigue and weight gain develop clinically because of reduced metabolic activity.<br><br>Levothyroxine normalizes TSH levels and restores physiological thyroid hormone effects.<br><br>Carbimazole (option A), radioiodine therapy (option B), thyroidectomy (option D), and potassium iodide (option C) are inappropriate routine treatments.<br><br><em>(Guyton and Hall Physiology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with De Quervain thyroiditis is treated primarily with:",o:["High-dose antithyroid drugs","Surgical thyroidectomy","Broad-spectrum chemotherapy","NSAIDs and steroids","Radioiodine ablation"],a:3,e:"De Quervain thyroiditis is usually a self-limiting inflammatory thyroid disorder. Fever and painful thyroid tenderness develop clinically after viral illness.<br><br>Anti-inflammatory treatment with NSAIDs or corticosteroids effectively relieves pain and inflammation.<br><br>Antithyroid drugs (option A), thyroidectomy (option B), chemotherapy (option C), and radioiodine ablation (option E) are unnecessary routinely.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with multinodular goiter suddenly develops hoarseness and hard fixation of the gland. The most important concern is:",o:["Graves disease","Acute hemorrhage only","Malignant transformation","De Quervain thyroiditis","Hyperparathyroidism"],a:2,e:"Sudden hard fixation and recurrent laryngeal nerve palsy in longstanding goiter strongly suggest malignancy. Hoarseness develops clinically because of nerve infiltration.<br><br>Anaplastic transformation should especially be considered in elderly patients with rapidly progressive symptoms.<br><br>Graves disease (option A), hemorrhage alone (option B), De Quervain thyroiditis (option D), and hyperparathyroidism (option E) are less likely explanations.<br><br><em>(Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with Graves disease is given Lugol iodine solution before surgery mainly to:",o:["Increase thyroid hormone release","Reduce gland vascularity","Produce hypothyroidism permanently","Destroy parathyroid glands","Prevent hypocalcemia"],a:1,e:"Lugol iodine decreases thyroid gland vascularity and hormone release before thyroid surgery. Intraoperative bleeding develops clinically less frequently after proper preparation.<br><br>The treatment also reduces gland friability, facilitating safer surgical dissection.<br><br>Increasing hormone release (option A), permanent hypothyroidism (option C), parathyroid destruction (option D), and hypocalcemia prevention (option E) are incorrect effects.<br><br><em>(Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
];